liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Reporting by Nicholas McElroy A former Queensland resident caught up in the conflict in the Middle East says authorities have told him there are no plans to get Australians out of Israel. Keanu Vicente lives in Israel but says he fled from Tel Aviv to Nazareth in the north of the country to avoid the shelling. "I was on the phone to the emergency Australian consular assistance today just asking them for any updates, at the time I called they told me they didn't have any plans for repatriation flights," he says. "The last 12 hours today, it's just been very tense with a lot of bad news pouring in from down south. "A lot of our friends and family lost a lot of people." He says he hid in bomb shelters in Tel Aviv on the day bombing broke out. "We woke up to the bombs and were hiding in the bomb shelters all day there," Mr Vicente says. He says many friends have been called into Israel's reserve forces in response to the conflict. "So that brings about a new sense of worry," he says.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Australian says it's 'tense' in Israel as friends are called up as reservists

Keanu Vicente
lives in Israel but says he fled from Tel Aviv to Nazareth in the north of the country to avoid the shelling.

"I was on the phone to the emergency Australian consular assistance today just asking them for any updates, at the time I called they told me they didn't have any plans for repatriation flights," he says.
"The last 12 hours today, it's just been very tense with a lot of bad news pouring in from down south.
"A lot of our friends and family lost a lot of people."
He says he hid in bomb shelters in Tel Aviv on the day bombing broke out.
"We woke up to the bombs and were hiding in the bomb shelters all day there," Mr Vicente says.
He says many friends have been called into Israel's reserve forces in response to the conflict.
"So that brings about a new sense of worry," he says.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: NSW Police Assistant Commissioner Tony Cooke said one person carrying a flag was arrested at Sydney Town Hall last night. He said the person was removed for their own safety and released. Assistant Commissioner Cooke defended advice from police for Israel supporters to stay away from the protest and denied he had any conversation with the New South Wales Police Minister about operational matters related to the protest. "This is very clearly an emotive issue across community," he said. "We continue to work across all communities. Absolutely. This is New South Wales. "We do not expect people to bring conflict from other places to the streets of Sydney and it will not be tolerated." He said an operation had been established to investigate what happened and identify people who committed offences. "I'm very disappointed in the strongest possible terms that people saw fit to utilise flares and whatnot," he said. "However, I can tell you the entire rally was covered by CCTV footage." liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: NSW Premier Chris Minns says he was horrified by the protest at the Sydney Opera House last night. "To celebrate what's happened in the Middle East in the last 48 hours is abhorrent," he told ABC News Breakfast. "I can't understand why the protest went ahead in any event. "The position of the New South Wales government is unambiguously clear — we lit up the Opera House in solidarity with the people of Israel and the Jewish community in New South Wales because we were as horrified as the rest of the community at the indiscriminate slaughter that took place in Israel." He said the situation was "obviously intolerable" for the Jewish community of New South Wales. "We cannot have a situation where members of the Jewish community feel that they can't and are being told not to participate in their city," he said. He said the decision to tell members of the Jewish community not to go to the Opera House was an "operational policing decision for the safety and security of the city". He said there were discussions happening between the government, police and the Jewish community. "The situation where they're told not to come into the city, despite it being an operational decision in a tight time frame, went ahead last night but that's intolerable for the future, and I know New South Wales police are talking with that community today and changes will be made." Watch the full interview below.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Minns says he 'can't understand' why protest at Sydney Opera House went ahead

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: If you need to vote via post in the referendum and haven't put in an application yet you need to get cracking! Postal vote applications close at 6pm local time tomorrow. The easiest way to put in an application is to do it online at the AEC website. In order for your postal vote to be counted, the AEC must receive your vote by the 13th day after referendum voting day — that will be October 27. But you need to complete your postal vote on or before voting day. Read more below about how to vote via post and who's eligible.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Reporting by Kimberley Price Collingwood Captain Darcy Moore says he will be voting Yes in this weekend's Voice to Parliament referendum. It follows fellow sports star, Panthers NRL Premiership hero Nathan Cleary also announcing his support for a First Nations Voice to Parliament. A week after winning the AFL Premiership, Darcy Moore told RN Breakfast host Patricia Karvelas that despite what some people thought, sport and politics could mix. "I'll be voting yes. To me, I feel like it's an intuitive next step and seems to be an important and practical way to help Indigenous Australians," he said. "There are certainly people out there that want you to shut up and play sport, but we've seen all around the country, like with Nathan Cleary, athletes are human beings and citizens of the country too, so they can exercise their right and say what they want to say and they can do it in a really healthy way. "The argument around division … to my mind there is already advisory bodies for Indigenous Australians that have come and gone as governments have changed. The mechanism has kind of already existed anyway, so by making it sort of permanent in the constitution, it's just locking it in. So in that way it's not anything new." Listen to the full interview below.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Collingwood captain Darcy Moore backs Yes vote on RN

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Speaking on ABC News Breakfast this morning, chairman of the Aboriginal Land Council of Tasmania Michael Mansell said that "saving a miracle" the Voice to Parliament is "dead in the water". "The referendum will be defeated on Saturday," he said. "The prime minister has said that he's not going to legislate after the referendum for a Voice to Parliament and so what we need to start doing is looking at, well, from Sunday onwards, where do we go? "We know that the prime minister has said he's going to implement the Uluru Statement in full, and we also know that there are 19 Closing The Gap targets that haven't been fulfilled, so there's plenty of work to do." Mr Mansell said that if the Voice to Parliament doesn't go through, he expects advocacy to continue. "I think rather than the prime minister allow the Yes camp to walk away bitterly disappointed with the outcome, feeling completely empty and hopeless because the whole thing came to nothing, [he] is going to have to offer that group some way to use their energies in the next 12 months."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Aboriginal leader Michael Mansell says Voice 'dead in the water'

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Why would the ACCC allow the Origin Energy takeover if it knows it could lessen competition? Because it thinks the public benefits of the takeover will more than make up for it. ACCC chair Gina Cass-Gottlieb says the acquisition will likely result in "an accelerated roll-out of renewable energy generation," and lead to "a more rapid reduction in Australia’s greenhouse gas emissions". “The Brookfield Global Transition Fund has been specifically established to focus on the transition to renewable energy," she said. "Its decision to buy Origin, Australia's fourth-largest emitter of greenhouse gases, is driven by a strong imperative and commercial incentive to lower emissions quickly. "In this case, we determined that the likely gains for Australia's renewable energy transition amount to a public benefit sufficient to outweigh the likely public detriments. "We drew extensively on our engagement with industry participants to weigh these public benefits and detriments," she said. She says the accelerated build-out of Origin's renewable energy generation would be a material benefit to the Australian public, because it would replace some fossil fuel generation earlier than would occur without the proposed acquisition. "The ACCC considers that a reduction in greenhouse gas emissions is a public benefit of considerable weight," she said. However, the ACCC also says there are several reasons why the benefits to the community may not be as large as suggested by the $20 billion to $30 billion build-out plan proposed by Brookfield. "These factors include constraints within the electricity transmission network, particularly in the short-term, which may delay Brookfield's ability to build renewable energy generation at the speed claimed," she said. "We also recognise that some of Brookfield's proposed renewable investments would be likely to be made by others if the acquisition does not eventuate."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: ACCC says Origin Energy takeover will accelerate the roll-out of renewable energy

children.content: Why would the ACCC allow the Origin Energy takeover if it knows it could lessen competition?
Because it thinks the public benefits of the takeover will more than make up for it.

ACCC chair Gina Cass-Gottlieb says the acquisition will likely result in "an accelerated roll-out of renewable energy generation," and lead to "a more rapid reduction in Australia’s greenhouse gas emissions".
“The Brookfield Global Transition Fund has been specifically established to focus on the transition to renewable energy," she said.
"Its decision to buy Origin, Australia's fourth-largest emitter of greenhouse gases, is driven by a strong imperative and commercial incentive to lower emissions quickly.
"In this case, we determined that the likely gains for Australia's renewable energy transition amount to a public benefit sufficient to outweigh the likely public detriments.
"We drew extensively on our engagement with industry participants to weigh these public benefits and detriments," she said.

She says the accelerated build-out of Origin's renewable energy generation would be a material benefit to the Australian public, because it would replace some fossil fuel generation earlier than would occur without the proposed acquisition.
"The ACCC considers that a reduction in greenhouse gas emissions is a public benefit of considerable weight," she said.
However, the ACCC also says there are several reasons why the benefits to the community may not be as large as suggested by the $20 billion to $30 billion build-out plan proposed by Brookfield.

"These factors include constraints within the electricity transmission network, particularly in the short-term, which may delay Brookfield's ability to build renewable energy generation at the speed claimed," she said.
"We also recognise that some of Brookfield's proposed renewable investments would be likely to be made by others if the acquisition does not eventuate."

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The Australian Competition and Consumer Commission (ACCC) has granted authorisation with conditions for the proposed acquisition of Origin Energy by Brookfield and MidOcean. And it's doing so despite admitting that it's not satisfied that the acquisition would not be likely to substantially lessen competition. The proposed acquisition comprises two interdependent transactions. The transactions will result in a consortium led by the Brookfield Global Transition Fund owning Origin’s energy markets business, including Origin’s electricity generation and electricity and gas retail businesses. MidOcean will own Origin’s upstream gas interests. Under the Competition and Consumer Act, the ACCC must not grant authorisation unless it is satisfied in all the circumstances that the proposed acquisition would not be likely to substantially lessen competition, or that the likely public benefits would outweigh the likely public detriments. But here's what the ACCC has to say about that. "On the first limb of the test, we are not satisfied that the proposed acquisition would not be likely to substantially lessen competition," ACCC chair Gina Cass-Gottlieb said. "However, after a detailed review, we are satisfied that the proposed acquisition is likely to result in public benefits that would outweigh the likely public detriments. "We found that the public benefits and public detriments in this matter were finely balanced. Likely detriments, particularly anti-competitive effects from vertical integration, had to be weighed against likely benefits to Australia's renewable energy transition. We considered undertakings offered by Brookfield, AusNet and MidOcean in this weighing process."

title.children: 'The most horrific death': Four pet dogs die with similar symptoms in same suburb

image.altText: A man crouching down in Australian bush while light smoke from a small fire rises behind him

items.synopsis: More bush could have been treated despite the wet weather of the last few years, according to Firesticks Alliance co-founder Victor Steffensen.

title.children: As bushfires devastate communities, one leader says a key preparation tool has been under-utilised

image.altText: Two boys and a man stand in front of a dirt jump BMX track

items.synopsis: Building trails, jumps and ramps out of dirt might be a nuisance for councils, but it's a source of pride for many young BMX riders. Riders and researchers want local governments to back the pastime of building tracks in approved places.

title.children: Riders 'take pride' in digging jumps. Now they want support to continue their work
